Background

In the data folder, you will find data about shark incidents in California between 1950-2022. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

Load the libraries

library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")

Load the data

Run the following code chunk to import the data. In this chunk, I am removing NAs.

sharks <- 
  read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv", 
           na=c("NA", "N/A", "Unknown", "NOT COUNTED", "", " ")) %>% 
  clean_names()

  1. Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents per county.
sharks %>% 
  group_by(county) %>% 
  count(county) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  head(5) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=county,y=n,fill=county))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(title = "Total Shark Incidents per County",
       x = "County",
       y = "Number of Incidents")

  1. How do the number and types of injuries compare by county? Make a table that shows the number of injury types by county. Which county has the highest number incidents? (hint: your table should be in wide format)
names(sharks)
##  [1] "incident_num"     "month"            "day"              "year"            
##  [5] "time"             "county"           "location"         "mode"            
##  [9] "injury"           "depth"            "species"          "comment"         
## [13] "longitude"        "latitude"         "confirmed_source" "wfl_case_number"
injury_by_county <- 
  sharks %>% 
  count(county,injury) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from=injury,
    values_from=n,
    values_fill=0
  )
  1. Use the table from #5 to make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by county.
injury_by_county %>% 
  mutate(total=rowSums(across(-county),na.rm=T))
## # A tibble: 22  9
##    county                minor  none major `minor*` `none*` fatal `major*` total
##    <chr>                 <int> <int> <int>    <int>   <int> <int>    <int> <dbl>
##  1 Del Norte                 2     1     0        0       0     0        0     3
##  2 Humboldt                  2     9     7        1       1     0        0    20
##  3 Island - Catalina         1     3     0        0       0     0        0     4
##  4 Island - Farallones       0     0     7        0       0     0        0     7
##  5 Island - San Miguel       2     0     2        0       0     1        0     5
##  6 Island - San Nicolas      1     0     0        0       0     0        0     1
##  7 Island - Santa Barba     0     0     0        0       0     0        1     1
##  8 Island - Santa Cruz       1     1     0        0       0     0        0     2
##  9 Island - Santa Rosa       0     0     1        0       0     0        0     1
## 10 Los Angeles               6     2     0        0       0     1        1    10
## #  12 more rows
injury_by_county %>% 
  mutate(total=rowSums(across(-county),na.rm=T)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=total,y=reorder(county,total),fill=county))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(title = "Total Shark Incidents by County",
       subtitle = "Calculated using across() and rowSums()",
       x = "Number of Incidents",
       y = "County")

Whits

  1. Are all incidents involving Great Whites fatal? Make a plot that shows the number and types of incidents for Great Whites only.
sharks %>% 
  filter(species=="White") %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=injury,fill=injury))+
  geom_bar()+
  labs(title = "Incidents Involving Great White Sharks",
       x = "Injury Type",
       y = "Count")

Although great white shark attacks have drawn attention, data shows that most of the incidents did not result in deaths, and in fact, a large proportion of people were not injured
